title: Resonance parameters of Ni-58 + n and Ni-60 + n from very high resolution transmission measurements

x4freetext: Resonance parameters of Ni-58 + n and Ni-60 + n from
very high resolution transmission measurements

x4codes.shortRef: Conf: Conf.on Nucl.Data for Sci.and Technol.,Juelich 1991, p.71 (1991)

x4freetext: Main ref.
Data submitted on diskette by
a Brusegan. Updated with two new measurements at 100
and 400 m for Ni-58. new analysis for both Ni-58 and
A.B., G.R., R.S., C.V der V., C.B., Z.E. and
experimental site.

x4codes.hlp: SCK CEN (Belgian Nuclear Research Centre), Mol, Belgium

x4freetext: F.P.,L.M.
University of Antwerp, G.V.
The 150 MeV Geel Linac, Gelina,
operated with burst width of 1 ns and a frequency
of 800 Hz, was used for the measurements.
.Uranium target, bombarded with 150 MeV electrons. The
neutrons were moderated immediately after the target
for the 50, 100 and 200 m transmission measurements.
.White neutron source.
.Three different samples were used. They were
sample        enrichment         thickness
(per-cent)           (at/b)
Time-of-flight techniques, with four neutron
flight paths with lengths ranging fron 50 to 400 m.
A B4C slab, containing 10-B, being 5 mm thick,
was used together with four 4 inch by 2 inch C6d6
scintillators to detect the neutrons in the 50 m
transmission measurements.
A 0.25 inch by 6 inch Li-glass detector, moun-
ted on a 5 inch EMI9823KQB PM tube, was used to detect
the neutrons in the 100 m transmission measurements.
One inch NE110 plastic scintillator, viewed by
four RCA 4516 PM tubes, was used to detect the neu-
trons in the 200 and 400 m transmission measurements.
.A B4C anti-overlap filter was permanently in the beam
to absorb low energy neutron from the previous burst.
In addition, the beam was filtered with 0.37 g/cm2 of
uranium at 100, 200 and 400 m.
A BF3 detector was used to normalize the
sample-in and sample-out runs.
.The experimental data were analysed with REFIT and
MULTI, using new potential scattering lengths and the
new resolution function calculated by Coceva (to be
published).
.The data were corrected for background and dead-time.
N.O.
SM: Subents 003,004,006,007 corrected.
SD:Updated to new date formats,lower case.
Meaningless zeros were deleted from the data. Illegal
space from author`s name deleted. ERR-ANALYS moved to
Subents 002,005.
The error is 15% of the quoted neutron width.
Spin J and angular momentum L is uncertain.
The neutron width was kept fixed in the analysis.
Spin and parity was taken from ORNL/TM-10841
ENDF-347 by C.M. Perey et al.
Combination of flag 2 and 4.
.REFIT was used to fit the energy region between 700 eV
and 30 keV, i.e. to determine the parameters of the
-105. keV, -11.8 keV, 13.3 keV, 13.6 keV and 15.3 keV
resonances and the S-wave radius. The P-wave radius
has been estimated in the minima of the cross-section
at about 400 keV and the D-wave radius in the minima
between 700 keV and 2 MeV.

x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: The error of the resonance energies are
given by MULTI to about 1.0e-05 * En(resonance), which
is of the order of the uncertainty in the moderation
distance.
The error in the neutron widths contain
1) the statistical error given by MULTI,
2) one half of the max. Variation of the width
observed when the timing component of the
resolution is adjusted,
3) one half of the max. Variation of the width
observed when nearby resonances are adjusted.
Data submitted on diskette by A. Brusegan.
Similar data in the Tbl. 3 of 91JUELIC,71.

fixed at 1 eV, except for the 2.2 keV resonance. REFIT
was used to analyse this resonance and to determine
the negative energy resonance and S-wave radius. The
P-wave radius was determined by the best fit of high
energy minima.
